        <mxCell id="TFBeAIytjmZ6rmNEA32S-15" value="&lt;h1&gt;Notes&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;1. Vault stores the wallet keys in an encrypted format with highest level of security&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;2. Hub databases does not store wallet keys directly, but it stores Vault encoded cypher string of a wallet&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;3. Hub can decypher the Vault encoded strings with the Vault token and vault access&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;4. To decypher the wallet keys, we need to have Secret 1 and Secret 2&lt;/p&gt;" style="text;html=1;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;spacing=5;spacingTop=-20;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" vertex="1" parent="1">
          <mxGeometry x="-290" y="670" width="450" height="180" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="TFBeAIytjmZ6rmNEA32S-16" value="&lt;h1&gt;Threats Eleminated&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;1. Hub cannot use the wallet keys without having Secret 1 and Secret 2&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;2. Due to the point 1, if someone has access to the Vault, he will not be able to see the wallet keys. So, no wallets are getting compromised.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;3. Hub server is not single point for cyber attacks. Cyber attackers need to target a specifc wallet also.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;4. To decypher every wallet, additional processing units will be required for the attackers.&lt;/p&gt;" style="text;html=1;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;spacing=5;spacingTop=-20;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" vertex="1" parent="1">
